I"ò<p>In this section, we will discuss the first order perturbation theory.</p>

<p>Consider the SchrÃ¶dinger equation for a Hamiltonian $\hat{H}^0$ with known eigenvalues $\{E^0_n\}$ and corresponding eigenvectors $\{\left|\psi_n\right&gt;\}$. Thus, they satisfy the equation</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\hat{H}^0 \left| \psi^0_n\right>  = E^0_n \left| \psi^0_n \right>.</script>

<p>In this section, we assume that the eigenvalues are nondegenerate; so there is one and only one eigenstate for each eigenvalue. We then look for how these energy eigenvalues and their states change when we change the Hamiltonian to $\hat{H} = \hat{H}^0 + \lambda \hat{H}â€™$.</p>

<div class="remark">
Remark: Note that when we do perturbation theory in quantum mechanics, we usually have that $\hat{H}'$ is a small Hamiltonian, and ramp the parameter $\lambda$ up to 1 at the end. So, $\lambda$ is used more as a bookkeeping device. In mathematics courses on asymptotic analysis/perturbation theory, one usually keeps $\lambda$ as a small parameter throughout the entire problem. 
</div>

<p>We define power series in $\lambda$ to approximately satisfy the equation for the full Hamiltonian</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\hat{H} \left| \psi_n\right>  = E_n \left| \psi_n \right>.</script>

<p>The power series are</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">E_n = \sum_{\ell=0}^\infty \lambda^\ell E^\ell_n</script>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\left|\psi_n\right> = \sum_{k=0}^\infty \lambda^k \left|\psi_n^k\right></script>

<p>where the notation $E^\ell_n$ means the $k$th correction to the $n$th eigenvalue, and the notation $\left|\psi_n^k\right&gt;$ means the $k$th correction to the $n$th eigenfunction. Letâ€™s plug these power series representations into the SchrÃ¶dinger equation.</p>

<h3 id="corrections-to-the-energy-eigenvalues">Corrections to the Energy Eigenvalues</h3>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">(\hat{H}^0 + \lambda\hat{H}') \sum_{k=0}^\infty \lambda^k \left|\psi_n^k\right> = \sum_{\ell=0}^\infty \lambda^\ell E^\ell_n \sum_{k=0}^\infty \lambda^k \left|\psi_n^k\right></script>

<p>Letâ€™s now collect terms at zeroth and first order. At zeroth order, we simply recover the unperturbed problem!</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">O(1):\quad  \hat{H}^0 \left| \psi_n^0\right> = E^0_n \left| \psi_n^0\right></script>

<p>At first order, we have the equation</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">O(\lambda): \quad \hat{H}^0 \left| \psi^1_n\right> + \hat{H}' \left|\psi^0_n\right> = E^1_n\left|\psi^0_n\right> + E^0_n\left|\psi^1_n\right></script>

<p>Now, letâ€™s act on the left with the bra $\left&lt;\psi^0_n\right|$.</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\left<\psi^0_n\right|\hat{H}^0 \left| \psi^1_n\right> + \left<\psi^0_n\right|\hat{H}' \left|\psi^0_n\right> = \left<\psi^0_n\right|E^1_n\left|\psi^0_n\right> + \left<\psi^0_n\right|E^0_n\left|\psi^1_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Since the Hamiltonian $\hat{H}^0$ is Hermitian, we can think of it as acting from the right on the bra $\left&lt;\psi^0_n\right|$, which means that</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\left<\psi^0_n\right|\hat{H}^0 \left| \psi^1_n\right> = \left<\psi^0_n\right|E^0_n\left|\psi^1_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Thus, the equation simplifies to</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\left<\psi^0_n\right|\hat{H}' \left|\psi^0_n\right> =E^1_n \left<\psi^0_n\right| \left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Since the states ${\left|\psi^0_n\right&gt;}$ are normalized, we simply get</p>

<div class="result">
Result: The first order correction to the $n$th eigenstate due to a perturbation Hamiltonian $\hat{H}'$ is

$$E^1_n = \left&lt;\psi^0_n\right|\hat{H}' \left|\psi^0_n\right&gt;$$

</div>

<p>Thus we have the first order corrections to the energies. Now, letâ€™s find the first order corrections to the eigenfunctions.</p>

<h3 id="corrections-to-the-eigenstates">Corrections to the Eigenstates</h3>
<p>To find the corrections to the eigenstates, letâ€™s return to the $O(\lambda)$ equation before we acted on it with the bra.</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\hat{H}^0 \left| \psi^1_n\right> + \hat{H}' \left|\psi^0_n\right> = E^1_n\left|\psi^0_n\right> + E^0_n\left|\psi^1_n\right></script>

<p>Letâ€™s rearrange it slightly</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">(\hat{H}^0 - E^0_n)\left|\psi^1_n\right> = (E^1_n - \hat{H}')\left|\psi^0_n\right></script>

<p>Now, letâ€™s expand the ket $\left|\psi^1_n\right&gt;$ in terms of the basis $\{\left|\psi^0_n\right&gt;\}$:</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\left|\psi^1_n\right> = \sum_{m\neq n} c_{mn}\left|\psi^0_m\right></script>

<p>now, all we need to do is find the coefficients $c_{mn}$. Note that the sum does not include $m=n$ because $(\hat{H}^0 - E^0_n)\left|\psi^0_n\right&gt; = 0$ anyways. Plugging this representation in,</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">(\hat{H}^0 - E^0_n)\sum_{m\neq n} c_{mn}\left|\psi^0_m\right> = (E^1_n - \hat{H}')\left|\psi^0_n\right></script>

<p>To isolate the constants $c_{mn}$, act with the bra $\left&lt;\psi^0_p\right|$ (where $p\neq n$) on both sides.</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\left<\psi^0_p\right|(\hat{H}^0 - E^0_n)\sum_{m\neq n} c_{mn}\left|\psi^0_m\right> = \left<\psi^0_p\right|(E^1_n - \hat{H}')\left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Letâ€™s simplify this to</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\sum_{m\neq n} \left<\psi^0_p\right|(\hat{H}^0 - E^0_n) c_{mn}\left|\psi^0_m\right> = \left<\psi^0_p\right|E^1_n\left|\psi^0_n\right> -  \left<\psi^0_p\right| \hat{H}'\left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Since $\left&lt;\psi^0_p\right|\hat{H}^0 = \left&lt;\psi^0_p\right|E^0_p$, this simplifies to</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\sum_{m\neq n} \left<\psi^0_p\right|(E^0_p - E^0_n) c_{mn}\left|\psi^0_m\right> = -  \left<\psi^0_p\right| \hat{H}'\left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>Finally, we get</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\sum_{m\neq n}(E^0_p - E^0_n) c_{mn}\delta_{pm}  = -  \left<\psi^0_p\right| \hat{H}'\left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

<p>which, because of the Kronecker delta, simplifies to</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
(E^0_p - E^0_n) c_{pn}  = -  \left<\psi^0_p\right| \hat{H}'\left|\psi^0_n\right> %]]></script>

